<ArticleLayout
  title="Bassinet vs Cot: Which One Makes Sense First?"
  description="Compare bassinets and cots for space, budget, mattress fit and age suitability, with Australian safety checks to make before buying."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-23"
  faqs={faqs}
  readingTime="5 minute read"
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery with a cot, change area and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    A bassinet takes up less room beside the bed but is used for a shorter stage. A cot needs more
    floor space and may work from the beginning through a much longer period. The better first
    purchase depends on what fits safely in your room, not on the assumption that every newborn
    needs both.
  </p>

  <h2>The difference at a glance</h2>
  <ComparisonTable rows={comparisonRows} caption="Comparison of a bassinet, cot and using both" />

  <h2>What fits beside the adult bed?</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the intended sleep area with drawers and doors open. Include access around the bed,
    curtains and blind cords, heaters, power points and any furniture that could make the position
    unsafe or awkward.
  </p>
  <p>
    A bassinet may suit a room that cannot accommodate a cot safely. Depending on the design, it
    may also be easier to move, but portability is useful only if the product remains stable and is
    approved for the way you intend to use it.
  </p>
  <p>
    A cot takes more room but avoids another sleep space transition if it fits from the start. Check
    its assembled dimensions rather than the packaging, then allow enough space to reach the baby
    and move through the room without squeezing past furniture.
  </p>

  <h2>The bassinet stage can be brief</h2>
  <p>
    The product's age, weight and developmental limits matter more than a general estimate of how
    many months it will last. ACCC guidance says bassinets and cradles are used only until the baby
    starts to roll, push up on hands or knees, or sit unaided. Stop sooner if the manufacturer's
    stated limit is reached.
  </p>
  <p>
    That may make the compact early setup worthwhile, but it also means budgeting for a second sleep
    space and deciding where the bassinet will go afterwards. If a cot fits safely from the
    beginning, buying both may solve no problem at all.
  </p>

  <h2>Count the whole setup, not just the frame</h2>
  <p>
    Compare the sleep space, correct mattress, fitted sheets and any replacement parts together.
    Avoid assuming an existing mattress will fit a different model. A mattress should be firm,
    flat and the correct size for the exact product.
  </p>
  <p>
    Using both can also mean duplicate linen, temporary storage and another adjustment to the room.
    Those costs may be reasonable when the bassinet solves a genuine space problem; they should not
    be treated as unavoidable newborn expenses.
  </p>

  <h2>Safety information should decide the purchase</h2>
  <p>
    The <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/settle-baby-to-sleep-safely/bassinets-and-cradles-guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC Product Safety bassinets and cradles guide</a>{" "}
    sets out current buying and use advice. Since 19 January 2026, new mandatory standards require
    bassinets and cradles supplied in Australia to carry visible warnings and come with instructions
    for safe assembly and use.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Check that the product is stable, complete and undamaged.</li>
    <li>Use the firm, flat mattress made to fit it snugly.</li>
    <li>Follow the assembly, maintenance and developmental-limit instructions.</li>
    <li>Keep the sleep space clear of pillows, bumpers, folded quilts, toys and sleep aids.</li>
    <li>Place it away from curtain cords, heaters, electrical appliances and decorative mobiles.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Read this alongside <a href="https://rednose.org.au/resources/safe-sleeping/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Red Nose safe sleeping guidance</a>{" "}
    and seek advice from a qualified health professional for the individual baby.
  </p>

  <h2>Second-hand needs a stricter check</h2>
  <p>
    Before borrowing or buying a used bassinet or cot, check the model, labels, instructions,
    recalls, condition and every part. Do not rely on a seller's description of the age or safety of
    the product. An unknown history, missing hardware, damage or the wrong mattress is a reason to
    leave it behind.
  </p>

  <h2>Buy the sleep space that works now</h2>
  <p>
    Choose a bassinet when its smaller footprint solves an early space problem and you are prepared
    for its limits. Choose a cot from the beginning when it fits safely and avoiding a second setup
    makes more sense. Buying both is reasonable only when each has a clear job in the home.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
